../../planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:11:### Step 1 - Freeze the endpoint, baseline criterion, and anti-conjugation rule
../../planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:13:This step is under-specified in exactly the place where the entire chain gets its objectivity. "Choose one inherited theorem-facing endpoint" is too loose. There are several plausible endpoints on the LEI/CKN floor, and the choice of endpoint already biases which reformulations can look useful. If the endpoint is picked before seeing any candidate behavior, the chain may overconstrain the search. If it is picked after informal exposure to candidates, the chain becomes selection-biased while pretending not to be.
../../planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:17:The anti-conjugation rule is directionally correct but still too rhetorical. Many exact reformulations are neither trivially conjugate nor genuinely new. They sit in the middle ground where the nonlinearity is redistributed but not obviously reduced. The current rule does not say how to classify those cases. That invites after-the-fact judgment rather than a reproducible criterion.
../../planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:35:The instruction to test the gain "before absolute values, generic inequalities, or reconstruction erase it" is dangerous if interpreted naively. Of course one wants to preserve structure before flattening it. But in this area, many mirages survive only until the first legitimate norm inequality. A gain that exists only before the standard estimate machinery is not necessarily a gain; it may just be a presentation artifact. This step needs a criterion for when a pre-inequality feature is robust enough to count.
../../planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:41:### Step 4 - Insert the surviving candidate into the inherited LEI / CKN ledger
../../planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:43:This is where the chain tries to become honest, and it is also where it is weakest. "Write one explicit localization or contradiction line" understates the complexity of endpoint insertion. LEI/CKN arguments do not usually hinge on a single line; they depend on a tightly coupled stack of local energy, pressure decomposition, scaling, covering, and compactness. A candidate that helps one displayed line can still fail because it wrecks admissibility or cannot be threaded through the rest of the proof skeleton.
../../planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:55:The phrase "compare the artifact directly against the frozen baseline criterion" is also unrealistic in many cases. If the artifact lives in a model regime, a symmetry-reduced setting, or a partially localized context, the comparison may be only indirect. The chain should either require an explicit transfer map from artifact to baseline, or admit that some artifacts are only obstruction-sharpening tools rather than promotional evidence.
