../../planning-runs/run-009/judgments/chain-02.md:5:The attack is directionally strong, but not uniformly correct. Its best points are that the original chain compresses too many distinct failure modes, understates how central the viscous and nonlocal obstacles are, and ties success too tightly to an inherited LEI / CKN-style proof interface. Its weakest move is to treat the whole chain as little more than a disguised demolition protocol. The original chain does contain real discipline: early admissibility gating, an explicit coercivity check, and a demand for a hard artifact are all good constraints.
../../planning-runs/run-009/judgments/chain-02.md:22:- The original chain treats "admits" too loosely for deformation-based observables on the suitable weak / LEI floor.
../../planning-runs/run-009/judgments/chain-02.md:23:- The Step 1 kill condition is too compressed; measurable definition, renormalized definition, approximation stability, and LEI-compatible compactness should be separated.
../../planning-runs/run-009/judgments/chain-02.md:66:This is one of the attack's strongest points. The original chain does not just test whether the observable has value; it tests whether it can be inserted into one inherited LEI / CKN architecture. That is too narrow. Failure against that architecture is evidence, but not automatic proof that the mechanism itself is dead.
../../planning-runs/run-009/judgments/chain-02.md:104:- The refined chain should still test inherited insertion, but only as one interface test, not as the only success criterion.
../../planning-runs/run-009/judgments/chain-02.md:151:- avoid treating inherited LEI / CKN insertion as the only legitimate theorem interface,
