../../planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-01.md:27:- Restricting to "mission-live sources only" is defensible for workflow discipline, but it creates a structural blind spot. If the mission's live sources are already biased toward Tao-sensitive geometric or transport-flavored mechanisms, this step cannot detect that the whole menu is path-dependent and incomplete.
../../planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-01.md:38:- Requiring one architecture per candidate is a strong anti-handwaving move. The problem is that the listed architectures are still broad labels: local criterion, transport-continuation, concentration exclusion, stochastic contradiction, critical-element rigidity. Each label hides several incompatible technical routes and bottlenecks.
../../planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-01.md:50:- The four axes are not commensurable. Tao sensitivity, endpoint closeness, prior-art distance, and narrowness of the first missing lemma measure different things and can point in opposite directions. A candidate close to an endpoint is often near prior art; a candidate far from prior art often has a very wide missing lemma. The chain offers no rule for handling these tradeoffs.
../../planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-01.md:52:- Prior-art distance is especially dangerous as a ranking axis. Distance from prior art is not evidence of truth or usefulness; often it is evidence that the route is underdeveloped. This axis can reward novelty theater unless heavily subordinated to bottleneck relevance.
