../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:7:The substantive problem is deeper. The chain is built around a deterministic stretching observable that is supposed to live on, or be honestly bridged back to, the suitable-weak / LEI theorem floor. That is exactly the point where transport-based ideas usually fail. If the observable is genuinely Lagrangian or deformation-tracking, then suitable-weak data is typically too weak to define it cleanly without importing regular Lagrangian flow machinery, extra spatial regularity, or a coarse-grained proxy whose bridge burden is already comparable to the hard theorem. The chain acknowledges this risk, but not ruthlessly enough. Much of the later structure is bookkeeping around an initial likely-false premise.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:11:### Step 1 - Freeze one admissible stretching observable, one framework, and one endpoint
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:15:- "Choose one observable only" sounds disciplined, but the menu given already hides the core issue: cumulative positive strain along trajectories, mollified deformation growth, and related stretching clocks do not live on the same analytic floor. Some are genuinely Lagrangian, some are coarse-grained Eulerian surrogates, and some implicitly assume enough regularity to make deformation tensors along paths meaningful. Treating them as interchangeable options understates the setup burden.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:16:- The fallback to "one stronger proxy class with a named bridge burden" is the main loophole. A named bridge is not the same thing as a plausible bridge. This lets the chain survive Step 1 by moving the hard problem into a proxy class and relabeling the unresolved descent back to suitable-weak / LEI as future debt.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:17:- The endpoint freeze is also too soft. "Local concentration exclusion by default, continuation only if the observable already behaves like norm control" sounds cautious, but it still assumes that a stretching observable is even aligned with a CKN-type exclusion mechanism. That alignment is not obvious. A quantity can track stretching and still fail to control the local energy or pressure terms that actually drive concentration arguments.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:28:- "Mark which pieces are exact on the chosen framework and which already assume extra regularity" is honest, but again too weak. If the key stretching-production term is exact only after introducing regularity that is unavailable on suitable-weak solutions, the chain should probably terminate here. The current wording leaves room for continuing with a largely formal identity plus a long debt register.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:37:- "Choose one concrete host bad term only" creates a cherry-picking risk. The Navier-Stokes obstruction is not usually one isolated bad term that can be neutralized in a vacuum. Positive stretching production, pressure transfer, and localization losses are coupled. Freezing one bad term can make the branch look more coercive than it is.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:39:- The proposed gain is also badly matched to the likely host bad term. A stretching observable often measures the same mechanism that makes the term dangerous. Tracking cumulative positive strain does not by itself force cancellation or one-sided control; it may simply repackage the instability.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:42:Concrete failure mode: the observable shows monotone growth precisely when stretching intensifies. Step 3 then mistakes correlation with the bad mechanism for leverage over it.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:48:- The whole branch only matters if the observable cashes out inside an actual LEI / CKN argument. That means surviving cutoff losses, pressure nonlocality, and any proxy-to-floor transfer simultaneously. Most transport-side ideas fail exactly here.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:50:- The step also hides a category mismatch. A trajectory-level or deformation-level observable is not automatically the right currency for an LEI / CKN line, which is built from localized energy, dissipation, and pressure structure. The branch still has not explained why the promoted quantity couples to the theorem-facing line in the correct units and scale.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:53:Concrete failure mode: the promoted inequality yields control of a mollified stretching clock on transport tubes, but after localization the pressure and commutator terms reintroduce exactly the uncontrolled concentration channel. No theorem-facing exclusion survives.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:60:- The artifact criterion is also too easy to game. A toy inequality on a reduced scenario or a lemma with hidden smoothness assumptions can satisfy the documentary requirement while proving very little about the actual theorem floor.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:61:- The Tao-style averaging check is not central. If the branch survives to an actual theorem-facing artifact, then robustness under Tao-style averaging is worth asking. But in practice the branch is much more likely to fail on admissibility, coercivity, or endpoint transfer first. Making Tao sensitivity a named late-stage screen risks importing a fashionable comparator instead of confronting the local analytic obstruction.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:70:- The positive branch still assumes that after all prior screens there will remain a meaningful conditional route with a "first narrower missing lemma." For this chain, the missing lemma is likely not narrow at all. It is more likely to be something like: define and control the chosen stretching observable on the theorem floor while transferring a local coercive gain through pressure and cutoff structure. That is not a narrow remainder; that is the problem.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:74:Concrete failure mode: the final memo presents a "conditional route" whose missing lemma is essentially a coercive deterministic stretching criterion on suitable-weak solutions strong enough to block concentration. That is just the original regularity barrier translated into new vocabulary.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:84:Everything depends on defining a deformation or stretching observable on suitable-weak / LEI data, or else on a proxy class with an honest descent back. That is not a technical detail. It is the core obstruction. The chain treats it as Step 1 setup plus Step 4 transfer debt, when it is really the dominant risk governing every later step.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:86:### 3. There is no serious novelty screen against prior art
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:88:Deterministic stretching, deformation tensors, and strain-based criteria are not unexplored territory. Without an explicit prior-art audit, this branch can easily reinvent known non-closing ideas: deformation-based blowup criteria, Lagrangian stretching heuristics, coarse-grained transport observables, or strain-alignment criteria that do not descend to theorem-facing estimates. A chain that wants to justify being "meaningfully different" should make novelty a gating condition, not an implicit hope.
../../planning-runs/run-010/attacks/chain-02.md:108:What is weak is the underlying bet. This chain is trying to get theorem-facing leverage out of a deterministic stretching observable in a regime where defining the observable, making it coercive, and transferring it through localization are all individually doubtful and jointly likely impossible. The most probable honest outcome is not a narrow positive route but an early obstruction: either the observable does not live on the theorem floor, or it lives only as a surrogate whose bridge cost is essentially the full problem, or it tracks stretching without controlling it.
